    description = 'A comprehensive legal treatise examining the Islamic family system through the lens of personal status law (Al-Ahwal Al-Shakhsiyyah), providing systematic coverage of Muslim family jurisprudence including marriage, divorce, inheritance, and child custody. This work synthesizes Quranic commandments, Prophetic traditions, and established jurisprudential principles to create a practical legal framework for governing family relations within Islamic society. The text addresses contemporary applications of traditional Islamic family law, including marriage contracts and procedures, various forms of divorce, inheritance calculations, custody arrangements, and financial obligations between family members. Through detailed analysis of both classical jurisprudential positions and modern legal codifications, the work demonstrates how Islamic family law principles can be effectively implemented in contemporary legal systems while maintaining fidelity to divine guidance and serving the welfare of Muslim families in diverse social contexts.'
